### Backend Real-time Events (Phase 3)

#### [NEW] [eventService.js](file:///C:/Users/anshu/OneDrive/Desktop/TrackPrep/server/src/services/eventService.js)
An event manager extending Node.js's native `EventEmitter`. It acts as the bridge between database services and real-time outputs. It provides an initialization hook for a Socket.io server to listen to actions and broadcast them to clients.

#### [NEW] [socket.js](file:///C:/Users/anshu/OneDrive/Desktop/TrackPrep/server/src/config/socket.js)
A setup configuration that dynamically checks if `'socket.io'` is installed. If installed, it binds Socket.io to the HTTP server and registers connection event hooks (rooms, messages) via `eventService`. If not installed, it yields a warnings-only stub, maintaining backward compatibility.

#### [MODIFY] [problemService.js](file:///C:/Users/anshu/OneDrive/Desktop/TrackPrep/server/src/services/problemService.js)
Import `eventService` and emit an event when a user solves a problem.

#### [MODIFY] [appService.js](file:///C:/Users/anshu/OneDrive/Desktop/TrackPrep/server/src/services/appService.js)
Import `eventService` and emit an event when a user logs an application.

#### [MODIFY] [taskService.js](file:///C:/Users/anshu/OneDrive/Desktop/TrackPrep/server/src/services/taskService.js)
Import `eventService` and emit an event when a user completes a task.

#### [MODIFY] [index.js](file:///C:/Users/anshu/OneDrive/Desktop/TrackPrep/server/src/index.js)
Import `setupSocketIO` and bind it to the running HTTP server.

